# scifi-mechanism-single-device-design — History

## v1.3.0 (2026-06-01)

**Changed by:** M55 reality-computes-itself offload mechanism design (Myrmidon swarm physics agent)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Bumped version to 1.3.0
- Added Class C (Reality Offload / Computational Universe) to mechanism class taxonomy
- Added "Key Pattern: Class C Offload Architecture (M55)" reference block
- Added "Real Citations Reusable for Computational-Universe / Information-Physics Mechanisms" section (6 citations: Lloyd PRL 2002, Lloyd 2006, Wheeler 1990, Deutsch 1985, Bekenstein 1973, Holevo 1973)
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: (1) claiming offload defeats Wall 7, (2) claiming full holographic readout at handheld power
- Updated Outcome in Overview table to mention M55
- Updated format reference recommendation: M14 preferred over M01 (most complete template)
- Updated Step 4 format notes: table-format walls, Feasibility Tags as table
- Added M55 row to Verified On table
- Added relevant tags: lloyd, wheeler, it-from-bit, computational-universe, offload-architecture, bekenstein, holevo, landauer, reality-computes

### Why
M55 (reality-computes-itself) design session produced a third distinct mechanism class -- the "offload to reality" approach -- which defeats Wall 4 (Feynman exponential) with zero new physics by refusing to simulate the region and running the region itself. The Lloyd/Wheeler/Deutsch/Bekenstein/Holevo citation set is independently reusable for any Class C mechanism. The two new Failed Attempts (Wall 7 inviolability for offload; impossibility of full holographic readout at practical power) are critical lessons for future Class C designs.

